{"id":"1911.11056","submitter":"Joseph Bowles","authors":"Joseph Bowles, Flavio Baccari, Alexia Salavrakos","title":"Bounding sets of sequential quantum correlations and device-independent\n  randomness certification","comments":"published version in Quantum","journal-ref":"Quantum 4, 344 (2020)","doi":"10.22331/q-2020-10-19-344","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  An important problem in quantum information theory is that of bounding sets\nof correlations that arise from making local measurements on entangled states\nof arbitrary dimension. Currently, the best-known method to tackle this problem\nis the NPA hierarchy; an infinite sequence of semidefinite programs that\nprovides increasingly tighter outer approximations to the desired set of\ncorrelations. In this work we consider a more general scenario in which one\nperforms sequences of local measurements on an entangled state of arbitrary\ndimension. We show that a simple adaptation of the original NPA hierarchy\nprovides an analogous hierarchy for this scenario, with comparable resource\nrequirements and convergence properties. We then use the method to tackle some\nproblems in device-independent quantum information. First, we show how one can\nrobustly certify over 2.3 bits of device-independent local randomness from a\ntwo-quibt state using a sequence of measurements, going beyond the theoretical\nmaximum of two bits that can be achieved with non-sequential measurements.\nFinally, we show tight upper bounds to two previously defined tasks in\nsequential Bell test scenarios.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Nov 2019 17:15:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 24 Feb 2020 11:51:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 23 Mar 2020 10:59:32 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 9 Oct 2020 15:02:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-21"}
