{"id":"1911.11197","submitter":"Josef Rukavicka","authors":"Josef Rukavicka","title":"Upper bound for the number of closed and privileged words","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.ipl.2020.105917","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DM math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A non-empty word $w$ is a border of the word $u$ if $\\vert w\\vert<\\vert\nu\\vert$ and $w$ is both a prefix and a suffix of $u$. A word $u$ with the\nborder $w$ is closed if $u$ has exactly two occurrences of $w$. A word $u$ is\nprivileged if $\\vert u\\vert\\leq 1$ or if $u$ contains a privileged border $w$\nthat appears exactly twice in $u$.\n  Peltom\\\"aki (2016) presented the following open problem: \"Give a nontrivial\nupper bound for $B(n)$\", where $B(n)$ denotes the number of privileged words of\nlength $n$. Let $D(n)$ denote the number of closed words of length $n$. Let\n$q>1$ be the size of the alphabet. We show that there is a positive real\nconstant $c$ such that \\[D(n)\\leq c\\ln{n}\\frac{q^{n}}{\\sqrt{n}}\\mbox{, where\n}n>1\\mbox{.}\\]\n  Privileged words are a subset of closed words, hence we show also an upper\nbound for the number of privileged words.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Nov 2019 20:02:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-01-22"}
